<subSubSection id="48D355CA8E6FFFE148A755A5FE0CFC31" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph id="007606418E6FFFE148A755A5FCDBFC6D" blockId="33.[151,1437,649,1106]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538E6FFFE148A755A5FE29FD51" bold="true" box="[151,396,649,674]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Description of Male.</emphasis>
Fully winged; length 
<quantity id="C731ABA48E6FFFE14ABF55A5FCBFFD51" box="[655,794,649,673]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="1.55" valueMax="1.6" valueMin="1.5">1.5–1.6 mm</quantity>
. Head brown, except mandible, clypeus and malar space testaceous; antenna testaceous-brown; mesosoma brown; metasoma brown-testaceous; legs testaceous. Antenna filiform; antennal segments in following proportions: 4:4:5:6:6:7:7:7:7:7. Head dull, granulated; frontal line complete; POL = 6; OL = 4; OOL = 3; OPL = 4; TL = 4; occipital carina complete. Scutum dull, granulated. Notauli complete, posteriorly separated. Scutellum and metanotum shiny, smooth, very slightly granulated. Propodeum with dorsal surface reticulate rugose; posterior surface with two distinct longitudinal keels and median and lateral areas reticulate rugose. Fore wing hyaline, without dark transverse bands. Basivolsella (
<figureCitation id="98F21AC48E6FFFE14CCB544DFAFDFC89" box="[1275,1368,865,889]" captionStart="PLATE 8" captionStartId="28.[151,233,1917,1940]" captionTargetBox="[174,1417,228,1844]" captionTargetId="figure-124@28.[151,1436,193,1896]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="PLATE 8. A–F, I, J. Male genitalia. G, H. Heads. A. Aphelopus nepalensis, paratype. B. A. niger from China. C. A. ochreus from China. D. A. orientalis from China. E. A. penanganus from Sabah. F. A. philippinus, holotype. G–I. A. querceus, female (G) and male (H) (from Olmi 1999a), holotype (I) (from Olmi 1984). J. A. rugidorsalis, holotype (from Xu et al. 1999a). Scale bar 0.15 mm for A and C, 0.20 mm for B and I, 0.18 mm for D, 0.13 mm for E and F, 0.23 mm for J." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5278396" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5278396/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Plate 8F</figureCitation>
) with two subdistal bristles and a small outer process. Tibial spurs 1/1/2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="007606418E6FFFE148F75485FE0CFC31" blockId="33.[151,1437,649,1106]" box="[199,425,937,961]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538E6FFFE148F75485FE80FC31" bold="true" box="[199,293,937,961]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
